Memgraph-local fixes for four UBSan-reported undefined behavior sites in
librdkafka 2.6.1. Each is independently verifiable; none are fixed in
master as of this writing, so a version bump won't drop the patch.

Per-hunk explanation:

1. src/rdvarint.h -- left shift of negative int64 in zig-zag varint encoder.

   `(num << 1)` on a negative int64_t is undefined per C11 6.5.7p4. UBSan
   reports it as `runtime error: left shift of negative value`. This is
   hit on every signed varint encode of a negative value; the Kafka v2
   record format and consumer-group protocol use -1 sentinels for things
   like leader epochs and offsets, so production traffic exercises it.
   Casting to uint64_t before shifting moves the operation into well-
   defined modular arithmetic; the bit pattern produced is unchanged on
   every two's-complement target.
   Annotation: none -- no new branch.
   Upstream: https://github.com/confluentinc/librdkafka/issues/5395

2. src/rdkafka.c -- initialize rk_ts_last_poll_start to rk_ts_created.

   The fields `rk_ts_last_poll_start` and `rk_ts_last_poll_end` are
   both left at 0 by struct creation. `rk_ts_last_poll_start` is then
   only ever written inside the `if (rk_ts_last_poll_end)` block of
   `rd_kafka_app_poll_start()` (rdkafka_int.h:1176).

   But that block is skipped on the very first call of every consumer:
   with `end` still 0, the body doesn't run, so `start` stays 0.
   `rd_kafka_app_polled()` then sets `end` to a wall-clock timestamp,
   not an interval. On the second call to `app_poll_start`, the block
   finally runs:

       idle_interval = end - start
                     = ~1.7e15 us - 0 = ~1.7e15  (wall-clock, not interval)

   `idle_interval * 1000000` then overflows int64_t. UBSan reports
   `runtime error: signed integer overflow` deterministically on every
   consumer's second poll, not after 107 days as the magnitudes might
   suggest. Even with overflow suppressed, the ratio is meaningless on
   that first sample: both intervals are wall-clock timestamps of
   roughly equal size, so poll_idle_ratio ~= 1000000 (~"100% idle")
   regardless of actual consumer behavior.

   Fix at the source: initialize `rk_ts_last_poll_start` to
   `rk->rk_ts_created` next to the existing `rk_ts_last_poll`
   initialization. Subsequent computations work in intervals from rk
   creation time, which are bounded by the consumer's actual lifetime
   and never produce overflow under any realistic workload.

   (In librdkafka master the same bug exists with the fields moved
   onto rd_kafka_q_t; the upstream PR initializes
   `rkq_ts_last_poll_start = rk->rk_ts_created` in
   `rd_kafka_q_init0()`.)

3. src/rdhdrhistogram.c -- clamp negative bucket index at source.

   `rd_hdr_getBucketIndex()` can return a negative bucket index when v
   is negative: the helper `bitLen(v | mask)` returns 0 for any
   signed-negative input (its `x >= 0x8000` check is false), and the
   computed bucket index `bitLen - unitMagnitude - subBucketHalfMag - 1`
   is then strictly negative.

   That negative bucketIdx then flows into four shift expressions in
   the same file, each of which is UB per C11 6.5.7p3/p4:
     - line 168 `(bucketIdx + 1) << subBucketHalfCountMagnitude`
     - line 212 `v >> (idx + unitMagnitude)`
     - line 219 `subBucketIdx << (bucketIdx + unitMagnitude)`
     - line 229 `1 << (unitMagnitude + adjustedBucket)`
   UBSan reports `runtime error: left shift of negative value` or
   `shift exponent is negative` depending on which path executes
   first.

   Reachable in librdkafka via any rd_avg_add() call that passes a
   negative value (e.g. a wrapped delta from signed-overflow upstream,
   or a non-monotonic clock subtraction).

   Fix at the source: clamp the bucket index to >= 0 in
   `rd_hdr_getBucketIndex()` itself. All four downstream shift
   expressions are then guaranteed non-negative shifts. Semantically
   matches "values below lowest discernible value belong in bucket 0".
   Verified with a 9-line UBSan reproducer; see the corresponding
   upstream commit on the fork branch for details.

4. src/rdkafka_metadata.c -- preserve err code on terminating path.

   `rd_kafka_parse_Metadata0()` documents that it "returns an error
   code on parse failure, else NO_ERROR" (docstring on the public
   wrapper). One path violates that contract: when the broker is
   terminating, line 514-516 sets `err = RD_KAFKA_RESP_ERR__DESTROY`
   and `goto done`. The `done:` label at line 1060 unconditionally
   returns RD_KAFKA_RESP_ERR_NO_ERROR, discarding the error code that
   was just set.

   The caller `rd_kafka_handle_Metadata()` then sees NO_ERROR, skips
   its `if (err) goto err;` check, and dereferences `&mdi->metadata`
   in the success branch. But `mdi` is NULL on this path (parse exits
   before `rd_tmpabuf_alloc` runs). `&NULL->metadata` is UB per
   C11 6.5.2.3; UBSan reports `member access within null pointer of
   type rd_kafka_metadata_internal_t`. In practice on every
   two's-complement target `&NULL->metadata` evaluates to NULL
   numerically (metadata is the first field), so the runtime impact
   is benign and production builds without UBSan won't notice it --
   the defect is formal UB rather than a crashing bug.

   The race is reachable in production, not only with the mock cluster.
   `rd_kafka_terminating()` is a lock-free atomic read; it can flip
   false->true between handle_Metadata's outer early-exit check and
   parse_Metadata0's inner check, so any application that calls
   `rd_kafka_destroy()` while a Metadata response is in flight can
   race into this state. Mock-cluster tests catch it deterministically
   because the in-process broker thread shortens the window
   dramatically; on real brokers the network round-trip widens it.

   Fix at the source: return `err` from `done:` instead of an
   unconditional NO_ERROR. On the success path `err` is still
   `RD_KAFKA_RESP_ERR_NO_ERROR` (initialized at line 490 and never
   reassigned in the success flow), so the return value is unchanged.
   On the terminating path `err` correctly propagates as `__DESTROY`,
   which engages the caller's existing `if (err) goto err;` branch --
   that branch already sets `md=NULL, mdi=NULL, rko_err=err` and
   replies to the requester, so no caller-side change is needed.

   The alternative of changing the terminating exit to `goto err`
   instead would require also initializing `tbuf` at declaration:
   `tbuf` is a local stack variable (rdkafka_metadata.c:473) without
   an initializer, and `rd_tmpabuf_new(&tbuf, ...)` only runs at
   line 535. The `err:` label unconditionally calls
   `rd_tmpabuf_destroy(&tbuf)` at line 1085, so routing the early
   terminating exit through `err:` would destroy an uninitialized
   struct. Every existing `goto err` site (lines 546, 800) is after
   `rd_tmpabuf_new`, which is why they're safe. Fixing `done:`
   instead is a one-line change with no such prerequisite.
   Annotation: none -- no new branch.

